# Lux Night - Engineering Rules & Conventions

## Project Overview
Lux Night is a Next.js 16 App Router application for discovering and booking premium nightlife experiences. Built with TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, and React 19.

## Tech Stack
- **Framework**: Next.js 16 App Router
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS with PostCSS build (no CDN)
- **UI Library**: React 19
- **Icons**: Material Symbols (Google Fonts)
- **Database & Auth**: Supabase (Auth, Postgres, RLS)
- **Payments**: Stripe (client/server split)
- **Routing**: Next.js App Router only (do not mock Next.js features or create custom routers)

## File Organization

### Directory Structure
```
app/                          # Next.js App Router pages and layouts
  (customer)/                 # Customer route group
    events/
      [id]/
        page.tsx
    wallet/
      page.tsx
    profile/
      page.tsx
  (staff)/                    # Staff route group
    dashboard/
      page.tsx
    tickets/
      page.tsx
  (merchant)/                 # Merchant route group
    events/
      [id]/
        page.tsx
    analytics/
      page.tsx
  (admin)/                    # Admin route group
    users/
      page.tsx
  api/                        # API routes
    stripe/
      checkout/
        route.ts
    events/
      route.ts
  layout.tsx                  # Root layout (server component)
  globals.css                 # Global styles

components/                   # Reusable components
  ui/                        # UI primitives (Button, Card, etc.)

contexts/                     # React Context providers
  [Name]Context.tsx

lib/                          # Utility functions
  supabase/
    client.ts                # Client-side Supabase client
    server.ts                # Server-side Supabase client
  stripe/
    client.ts                # Stripe client utilities
    server.ts                # Stripe server actions

types.ts                      # Shared TypeScript types and enums
constants.ts                  # Constants and configurations
```

### File Naming
- **Pages**: `page.tsx` (Next.js convention)
- **Components**: PascalCase (e.g., `Button.tsx`, `EventCard.tsx`)
- **Contexts**: `[Name]Context.tsx` (e.g., `AuthContext.tsx`)
- **Types**: `types.ts` (shared types) or co-located `types.ts`
- **Constants**: `constants.ts` or `[feature].constants.ts`

## Component Patterns

### Client vs Server Components
- **Default**: Server Components (no directive needed)
- **Client Components**: MUST add `'use client'` at the top of the file when using:
  - Hooks (useState, useEffect, useContext, etc.)
  - Event handlers (onClick, onChange, etc.)
  - Browser APIs (localStorage, window, etc.)
  - Context consumers

### Component Structure
```typescript
'use client'; // Only if client component

import React from 'react';
import Link from 'next/link';

interface ComponentProps {
  // Props definition
}

export default function ComponentName({ props }: ComponentProps) {
  // Component logic
  return (
    // JSX
  );
}
```

### Component Conventions
- Use default export for pages and main components
- Use named exports for utilities and hooks
- Props interfaces extend HTML element attributes when appropriate
- Always provide TypeScript types for props

### Context Pattern
```typescript
'use client';

import React, { createContext, useContext, ReactNode } from 'react';

interface ContextType {
  // Context shape
}

const Context = createContext<ContextType | undefined>(undefined);

export const Provider: React.FC<{ children: ReactNode }> = ({ children }) => {
  // Provider logic
  return (
    <Context.Provider value={/* value */}>
      {children}
    </Context.Provider>
  );
};

export const useContext = () => {
  const context = useContext(Context);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error('useContext must be used within Provider');
  }
  return context;
};
```

## Styling with Tailwind CSS

### Design System Colors
Use semantic color names from `tailwind.config.ts`:
- `primary` / `primary-hover` - Gold accent (#c8ab5f)
- `background-light` / `background-dark` - Theme backgrounds
- `surface-dark` / `surface-light` - Card/container surfaces
- `lux-gold` - Premium gold (#E8B94B)
- `lux-card` - Card backgrounds (#1E2224)
- `alert-red` - Error states (#D45D5D)

### Responsive Design
- **Mobile-first**: Design for mobile (`max-w-md mx-auto`)
- Use Tailwind responsive prefixes when needed (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`)
- Containers: `max-w-md mx-auto` for centered mobile layouts

### Dark Mode
- Always support dark mode using `dark:` prefix
- Use semantic color tokens (e.g., `bg-background-light dark:bg-background-dark`)
- Test both light and dark modes

### Utility Classes
- Use `no-scrollbar` class to hide scrollbars
- Use Material Symbols with `material-symbols-outlined` class
- Add `filled` class for filled icons: `material-symbols-outlined filled`

### Common Patterns
```tsx
// Container with max-width
<div className="relative w-full max-w-md mx-auto min-h-screen">

// Dark mode support
<div className="bg-background-light dark:bg-background-dark">

// Transitions
<button className="transition-all duration-300 active:scale-95">

// Backdrop blur
<div className="backdrop-blur-xl bg-background-dark/90">
```

## Routing & Navigation

### Route Groups by Role
**CRITICAL**: Organize routes by role using route groups `(role)`:
- `(customer)/` - Customer-facing routes
- `(staff)/` - Staff dashboard and operations
- `(merchant)/` - Merchant management
- `(admin)/` - Admin panel

Route groups are for organization only and do not appear in the URL.

**Examples**:
```
app/(customer)/events/[id]/page.tsx    �?URL: /events/[id]
app/(staff)/tickets/scan/page.tsx      �?URL: /tickets/scan
app/(merchant)/events/[id]/edit/page.tsx �?URL: /events/[id]/edit
```

### Next.js App Router Rules
- **ONLY use `app/` directory** - Do not use `pages/` directory
- **DO NOT mock Next.js features** - Use real Next.js routing, navigation, and APIs
- **DO NOT create custom routers** - Use Next.js built-in routing
- Use `next/link` for client-side navigation
- Use `useRouter` from `next/navigation` (not `next/router`)
- Use `useSearchParams` for query parameters
- Dynamic routes: `app/[id]/page.tsx` receives `params: { id: string }`

### Link Usage
```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';

<Link href="/events/123" className="...">
  Event Details
</Link>
```

### Router Hooks (Client Components Only)
```tsx
'use client';

import { useRouter, useSearchParams } from 'next/navigation';

const router = useRouter();
router.push('/path');
router.back();

const searchParams = useSearchParams();
const value = searchParams.get('key');
```

## State Management

### Local State
- Use `useState` for component-local state
- Use descriptive state variable names: `isOpen`, `activeTab`, `selectedEvent`
- State updaters: `setIsOpen`, `setActiveTab`

### Global State
- Use React Context for global state (auth, theme, etc.)
- Contexts live in `contexts/` directory
- Always provide error handling in context hooks

### State Patterns
```typescript
// Typed state
const [activeTab, setActiveTab] = useState<'bars' | 'events'>('events');

// Record/Object state
const [selections, setSelections] = useState<Record<string, number>>({});

// State updater pattern
const updateQuantity = (id: string, delta: number) => {
  setSelections((prev) => ({
    ...prev,
    [id]: Math.max(0, (prev[id] || 0) + delta)
  }));
};
```

## TypeScript Conventions

### Types
- Define shared types in `types.ts`
- Use enums for constants: `enum UserRole { CUSTOMER = 'customer' }`
- Use interfaces for object shapes
- Use type aliases for unions and complex types

### Type Safety
- Always type function parameters and return values
- Use type assertions sparingly
- Prefer type narrowing over assertions
- Use `Record<K, V>` for object maps

### Common Types
```typescript
// Props
interface ComponentProps {
  id: string;
  optional?: number;
}

// Event handlers
type HandleClick = (id: string) => void;

// State types
type Status = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';
```

## Code Style

### Imports
1. React imports
2. Next.js imports (next/link, next/navigation)
3. Third-party imports
4. Local imports (components, contexts, utils, constants, types)
5. Relative imports (../../../)

### Comments
- Use `//` for single-line comments
- Use `{/* */}` for JSX comments
- Mark TODOs: `// TODO: Connect to Supabase`
- Use descriptive comments for complex logic

### Function Naming
- Event handlers: `handle[Action]` (e.g., `handleSubmit`, `handleRegionSelect`)
- Toggle functions: `toggle[State]` or `set[State]`
- Utility functions: descriptive verb (e.g., `calculateTotal`, `formatDate`)

### JSX Structure
- Use semantic HTML elements (`header`, `main`, `section`, `article`)
- Add comments for major sections: `{/* Header */}`, `{/* Content */}`
- Use className template literals for conditional classes:
  ```tsx
  className={`base ${condition ? 'active' : 'inactive'}`}
  ```

## UI Component Patterns

### Button Component
Always use the shared `Button` component from `components/ui/Button.tsx`:
```tsx
import Button from '@/components/ui/Button';

<Button variant="primary" icon="arrow_forward" fullWidth>
  Submit
</Button>
```

Variants: `primary`, `secondary`, `outline`, `danger`

### Material Icons
```tsx
// Outline icon
<span className="material-symbols-outlined">home</span>

// Filled icon
<span className="material-symbols-outlined filled">star</span>
```

## Error Handling

### Context Errors
Always throw errors in context hooks when used outside provider:
```typescript
export const useAuth = () => {
  const context = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error('useAuth must be used within AuthProvider');
  }
  return context;
};
```

### Async Functions
- Use try/catch for async operations
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Handle loading and error states in UI

## Best Practices

### Performance
- Use React.memo for expensive components
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Lazy load heavy components when needed

### Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Provide alt text for images
- Ensure keyboard navigation works
- Maintain proper heading hierarchy

### Code Quality
- Keep components focused and single-purpose
- Extract reusable logic into hooks
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Follow the existing code patterns in the codebase

### Data Fetching Patterns

**CRITICAL**: All data fetching MUST include loading, empty, and error states.

#### Server Component Data Fetching
```tsx
// app/events/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/server';

export default async function EventsPage() {
  const supabase = createClient();
  
  // TODO: Replace with Supabase query
  const { data: events, error } = await supabase
    .from('events')
    .select('*')
    .order('created_at', { ascending: false });

  if (error) {
    // Handle error state
    return <ErrorState error={error} />;
  }

  if (!events || events.length === 0) {
    // Handle empty state
    return <EmptyState />;
  }

  return (
    <div>
      {events.map(event => (
        <EventCard key={event.id} event={event} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

#### Client Component Data Fetching with Loading States
```tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/client';

export default function EventsList() {
  const [events, setEvents] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchEvents() {
      try {
        setLoading(true);
        const supabase = createClient();
        // TODO: Replace with Supabase query
        const { data, error } = await supabase
          .from('events')
          .select('*');

        if (error) throw error;
        setEvents(data);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err.message);
      } finally {
        setLoading(false);
      }
    }
    fetchEvents();
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <LoadingState />;
  if (error) return <ErrorState error={error} />;
  if (!events || events.length === 0) return <EmptyState />;

  return (
    <div>
      {events.map(event => (
        <EventCard key={event.id} event={event} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

#### Backend Wiring Markers
- **ALWAYS mark backend wiring with TODO comments**:
  ```tsx
  // TODO: Connect to Supabase - Replace mock data
  // TODO: Implement RLS policy check
  // TODO: Add error handling for Supabase queries
  // TODO: Wire Stripe checkout session creation
  ```

#### Loading, Empty, and Error State Components
Every data-fetching component must handle:
1. **Loading**: Show skeleton or spinner
2. **Empty**: Show empty state message/action
3. **Error**: Show error message with retry option

```tsx
// Example loading state
if (loading) {
  return (
    <div className="flex items-center justify-center p-8">
      <div className="animate-spin rounded-full h-8 w-8 border-b-2 border-primary"></div>
    </div>
  );
}

// Example empty state
if (!data || data.length === 0) {
  return (
    <div className="text-center p-8 text-gray-500">
      <p>No events found.</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// Example error state
if (error) {
  return (
    <div className="text-center p-8 text-alert-red">
      <p>Error: {error.message}</p>
      <button onClick={retry}>Try Again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

